The article discusses the significance of Juneteenth, a holiday celebrated on June 19th to commemorate the emancipation of slaves in the United States. On this day in 1865, Major General Gordon Granger issued General Order Number 3, declaring that all slaves in Texas were free. This order brought the message of President Abraham Lincoln's Emancipation Proclamation to Texas, freeing thousands of slaves who were still in bondage. Six months later, the Thirteenth Amendment was ratified, officially abolishing slavery in the United States. Juneteenth has become an opportunity for African Americans to celebrate equality and liberty. The article also highlights the contributions of African Americans to American society and emphasizes the importance of upholding the rights of all Americans.